in","meanings":["Swedish: soldier's name, from Swedish <i>karbin</i> ‘carbine’, a type of short rifle or musket used by cavalry.","Cornish: hypercorrect backformation from Cornish <i>carr-bons</i> ‘causeway’, or a habitational name from Carbis in Lelant (Cornwall), of the same derivation.","English: variant of   Corbin  ."]},{"name":"Corvin","meanings":["English (Durham): possibly a variant of   Corbin  .","Altered form of Scottish, Irish or English   Colvin  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Korving</b> (mainly The Hague): from the personal name <i>Korving</i>, from <i>Corvinus</i>, from Latin <i>corvus</i> ‘raven’."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":43,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":52,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Corbie I was born in 1285, in England as the son of Corbie. He married Joan England Of England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1345, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1285–1345":"1285–1345","1310–1385":"1310–1385","–Male":"Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1385":"1385","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Boughton Malherbe, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Boughton Malherbe, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1285–1345":"1285–1345","1310–1385":"1